{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/feverish-children-management/background-information/definition/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"5f6ceb9a-b676-5cd4-9a24-6f3b4f288e91","slug":"definition","fullItemName":"Definition","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field 8e6932a8-67b6-475a-a021-6bf7c7c7bba0 --><h2>What is the definition of fever?</h2><!-- end field 8e6932a8-67b6-475a-a021-6bf7c7c7bba0 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item a8e7bb11-cb60-4c39-94f9-966f7729b559 --><!-- begin field 5a09a8b3-d3d1-46b3-bb19-11237180f032 --><ul><li>Fever represents a regulated rise in body temperature. An infant or child is considered to have a fever if their temperature is 38°C or higher.<ul><li>The National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) defines a fever as 'an elevation of body temperature above the normal daily variation'. It recognizes that this is often hard to define, as normal temperature varies depending on the person, the body site where temperature is measured, and the time of day (body temperature is normally lowest in the early morning and highest in the early evening).</li></ul></li><li>Measured and reported parental perception of fever should be accepted as a valid indicator of fever.</li><li>Feverish illness in young children usually indicates an underlying infection, and fever is part of the body's natural response to this.<ul><li>It is theorized that fever may inhibit bacterial and viral replication and strengthen the body's immune response to pathogens.</li><li>In a minority of children, fever may be due to a non-infectious condition such as Kawasaki disease or malignancy.</li></ul></li></ul><p>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/feverish-children-management/references/\">Ishimine, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/feverish-children-management/references/\">Richardson, 2015</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/feverish-children-management/references/\">Mace, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/feverish-children-management/references/\">NICE, 2017</a>]</p><!-- end field 5a09a8b3-d3d1-46b3-bb19-11237180f032 --><!-- end item a8e7bb11-cb60-4c39-94f9-966f7729b559 -->","topic":{"id":"57afe72a-44a7-59f4-8b36-6eb7a2a98627","topicId":"cad66ea8-fd1e-4e8e-8a0a-4373743b9757","topicName":"Feverish children - management","slug":"feverish-children-management","lastRevised":"Last revised in December 2018","chapters":[{"id":"37563924-9b7f-5010-ac82-0a34cfebfade","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"d6888baa-d127-575e-8a84-9dc99c5a3fc7","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"cd28b465-db51-5aaa-a791-4edb2d2190b9","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"2d5e04dc-f0b0-5c21-8aa0-e3dae4707252","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"214e8c64-9ed6-54f9-80fc-05f388a4efad","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"bc5b7055-3b0e-5b8e-af94-087af7c8df52","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"8a12ce09-3e70-5d55-a94e-0bb219807058","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"8fb8cc12-0b57-52bd-81a1-f665491b6461","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"e816954e-05aa-518b-9149-859f2eddaf82","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"80058d93-ee7d-5b6b-9999-cb059bb153ca","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"803d1dc1-882b-5b81-81e0-50f6ea2042a2","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"daec1f52-f8e3-5f92-9eeb-3f00896c0fc9","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"c06763f6